{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539529","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539529"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:42:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:42:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16657"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16657"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.29,0.61,0.05,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9348"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66174"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9348","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9348"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16657"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51622"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"377"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"1793"},{"type":"tags","id":"4124"},{"type":"tags","id":"4125"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22133"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39650"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43637"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66174"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for advice regarding cancer risk. Her mother died of ovarian cancer at age 45, and her maternal aunt was diagnosed with breast cancer at age 38. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She works as an accountant and has two children. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Clinical breast examination reveals no abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EYou discuss genetic testing options with her.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following genetic mutations is associated with the highest lifetime risk of ovarian cancer?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["MLH1","BRCA2","BRCA1","TP53","PTEN"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s family history suggests hereditary breast and ovarian cancer syndrome, warranting consideration of genetic testing. Understanding the different cancer risks associated with various mutations is crucial for appropriate counselling and management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBRCA1\u003C/strong\u003E mutation carriers have the highest lifetime risk of ovarian cancer, ranging from 40-60%. These cancers typically occur at a younger age (average 50 years) compared to sporadic ovarian cancer. BRCA1-associated breast cancers are more likely to be triple-negative.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBRCA2\u003C/strong\u003E mutations are associated with a lower lifetime ovarian cancer risk of 10-30%. These cancers tend to occur later in life. BRCA2-associated breast cancers are more likely to be hormone receptor-positive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMLH1\u003C/strong\u003E mutations are associated with Lynch syndrome, which carries a slightly increased risk of ovarian cancer (approximately 10%) but is primarily associated with colorectal cancer risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPTEN\u003C/strong\u003E mutations cause Cowden syndrome, which is primarily associated with breast cancer risk but not significantly increased ovarian cancer risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETP53\u003C/strong\u003E mutations cause Li-Fraumeni syndrome, which is associated with multiple cancer types including breast cancer, but not significantly increased ovarian cancer risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven this patient\u0027s family history, referral for genetic counselling would be appropriate to discuss testing options, risk management strategies, and surveillance recommendations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["BRCA1 mutation carriers have a higher lifetime risk of ovarian cancer (40-60%) compared to BRCA2 mutation carriers (10-30%).","Both BRCA1 and BRCA2 mutations significantly increase breast cancer risk, but the age of onset and cancer subtypes differ.","Genetic counselling is essential for individuals with family history of breast or ovarian cancer to discuss testing and risk management."],"references":["National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE). Familial breast cancer: classification, care and managing breast cancer and related risks in people with a family history of breast cancer [Internet]. NICE guideline CG164. London: NICE; 2013 [updated 2023 Nov 14; cited 2024 Nov 29]. Available from: https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/cg164","Neff RT, Senter L, Salani R. BRCA mutation in ovarian cancer: testing, implications and treatment considerations. Ther Adv Med Oncol. 2017 Aug;9(8):519-531. doi: 10.1177/1758834017714993. Epub 2017 Jun 19. PMID: 28794804; PMCID: PMC5524247.","Ramus SJ, Gayther SA. The contribution of BRCA1 and BRCA2 to ovarian cancer. Mol Oncol. 2009 Apr;3(2):138-50. doi: 10.1016/j.molonc.2009.02.001. Epub 2009 Feb 10. PMID: 19383375; PMCID: PMC5527889."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51622"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16657"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51622","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51622"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-29T13:09:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-24T18:41:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9348"}